Since $AD=BD=CD$, we know that triangle $ABC$ is isosceles. Given that $\angle BCA = 40^\circ$, we can use the fact that the sum of the angles in an isosceles triangle is always $180^\circ$. Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\angle ACB + \angle BCA + \angle CAB &= 180^\circ \\
\angle ACB + 40^\circ + \angle CAB &= 180^\circ \\
\angle ACB &= 180^\circ - 40^\circ - \angle CAB \\
\angle ACB &= 140^\circ - \angle CAB.
\end{align*}
Since $ABC$ is isosceles, we know that $\angle ACB = \angle CAB$. Thus,
\begin{align*}
\angle ACB &= 140^\circ - \angle CAB \\
2\angle ACB &= 140^\circ - \angle CAB \\
\angle ACB &= \frac{140^\circ}{2} - \angle CAB \\
\angle ACB &= 70^\circ - \angle CAB.
\end{align*}
We are given that $\angle BCA = 40^\circ$. Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\angle CAB &= 180^\circ - \angle BCA - \angle ACB \\
\angle CAB &= 180^\circ - 40^\circ - 70^\circ \\
\angle CAB &= 70^\circ.
\end{align*}
Substituting this into our previous equation, we get
\begin{align*}
\angle ACB &= \frac{140^\circ}{2} - 70^\circ \\
\angle ACB &= 70^\circ.
\end{align*}
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\angle BAC &= \angle ACB + \angle BCA \\
\angle BAC &= 70^\circ + 40^\circ \\
\angle BAC &= \boxed{110^\circ}.
\end{align*}

