We start by using the identity $\arccos x + \arccos y + \arccos z = \arccos \sqrt{xyz}$ to simplify the left-hand side of the equation:
\begin{align*}
\arccos x + \arccos 2x + \arccos 3x &= \arccos \sqrt{x(2x)(3x)} \\
&= \arccos \sqrt{6x^2} \\
&= \arccos \sqrt{6}x.
\end{align*}
Now we can substitute this expression into the original equation:
\begin{align*}
\arccos \sqrt{6}x &= \pi \\
\sqrt{6}x &= \pi^2 \\
x &= \frac{\pi^2}{\sqrt{6}}.
\end{align*}
Next, we substitute this value of $x$ into the equation for the cubic polynomial:
\begin{align*}
a\left(\frac{\pi^2}{\sqrt{6}}\right)^3 + b\left(\frac{\pi^2}{\sqrt{6}}\right)^2 + c\left(\frac{\pi^2}{\sqrt{6}}\right) + d &= 0 \\
\frac{\pi^6}{\sqrt{6}} + \frac{\pi^4}{\sqrt{6}} + \frac{\pi^2}{\sqrt{6}} + d &= 0.
\end{align*}
We can see that the only way to satisfy this equation is if $a=1,$ $b=1,$ $c=-1,$ and $d=0.$ Therefore, the smallest possible value of $|a| + |b| + |c| + |d|$ is
\begin{align*}
|a| + |b| + |c| + |d| &= |1| + |1| + |-1| + |0| \\
&= 2.
\end{align*}
Therefore, the smallest possible value of $|a| + |b| + |c| + |d|$ is $\boxed{2}.$

