We can start by finding the critical points of $f(x)$ by taking the derivative of $f(x)$ and setting it equal to zero:

\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= 2(\arccos x)^2 + 2(\arcsin x)^2 \\
&= 2x^2 + 2x^2 \\
&= 4x^2.
\end{align*}

Setting $f'(x) = 0$ gives us $x = 0$. Now we can test the endpoints of the interval $[0, 2\pi]$ to see if they are in the range of $f(x)$:

\begin{align*}
f(0) &= (\arccos 0)^2 + (\arcsin 0)^2 \\
&= 0 + 0 \\
&= 0.
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
f(2\pi) &= (\arccos 2\pi)^2 + (\arcsin 2\pi)^2 \\
&= 0 + 0 \\
&= 0.
\end{align*}

Since $f(0) = f(2\pi) = 0$, the range of $f(x)$ is $[0, 0]$. Therefore,

\boxed{The range of $f(x)$ is $[0, 0]$.}.

