Let's denote the matrix $\mathbf{M}$ as $\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix}.$ Then, we have the following system of equations:
\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 9 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \\
\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix} &= \begin{pmatrix} a & b \\ c & d \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}
Solving this system of equations, we get $a = 3, b = 2, c = -1, d = 2.$ Therefore, $\mathbf{M} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 & 2 \\ -1 & 2 \end{pmatrix}.$

Now, let's find the image of the line $y = 2x + 1$ under $\mathbf{M}.$ We can write the equation of the line in matrix form as $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 & 2 \\ -1 & 2 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}.$ Solving for $y,$ we get $y = 2x + 1.$

Therefore, the image of the line $y = 2x + 1$ under $\mathbf{M}$ is the line $y = 2x + 1.$

